Identity federation.

Federation lets external identities assume I-A-M roles without ever becoming I-A-M users. No per-person user, no long-lived password. Two protocols cover it. SAML two-point-zero, for enterprise identity providers like A-D-F-S, Okta, and Ping, using the assume-role-with-SAML call. And O-I-D-C, for Cognito, Google, E-K-S service accounts, and GitHub Actions, using assume-role-with-web-identity. In both cases the external identity proves itself to the identity provider, and AWS vends a short-lived role session in return.

The modern, preferred way to wire this across an organization is I-A-M Identity Center, formerly known as AWS single sign-on. It lives in your management account and connects to one source of truth: its own directory, Active Directory, or an external provider like Okta or Entra I-D. Users get one sign-on portal listing every account and role they're allowed to use, and behind the scenes Identity Center calls assume-role and hands them temporary credentials.

Its unit of authorization is the permission set: a template bundling A-W-S-managed and customer-managed policies, an optional boundary, and an optional session duration. You define it once and assign it to users in specific accounts. Identity Center then provisions a hidden I-A-M role into each target account, and when you update the permission set, that role updates everywhere it's assigned. New AWS environments today should default to Identity Center over per-account I-A-M users, because it eliminates the whole category of long-lived console passwords and access keys.
